{"key":"processedPost-6619942","value":{"id":6619942,"first":6619914,"last":6620056,"when":1172683579,"utime":"02/28/07 07:26 PM","content":"They'll fruit just fine at 80F.  You don't cold shock cubes unless you're trying to delay harvest.  They're a tropical species that fruits in warm weather.  In fact, cubes will fruit at temperatures into the 90's, which would easily cause a colonizing jar to develop wet spot and other contaminants.  Fruiting temperature can be higher than incubation temperature, although cooler fruiting temps provide a higher quality product.<br /><br />If you're using a small tub, you can freeze blocks of ice to put inside.<br />RR","title":"Re: temperature issues"}}